Let the rhombus be $ABCD,$ where $AB = BC = CD = DA = 51.$  Let $AC$ be the longer diagonal, and $BD$ be the shorter diagonal.  Let $E$ be the foot of the perpendicular from $B$ to $AC.$

[asy]
unitsize (0.2 cm);

pair A, B, C, D, E;

B = (0,0);
C = rotate(30)*(51,0);
D = rotate(60)*(0,51);
A = rotate(90)*(51,0);
E = foot(B,A,C);

draw(A--B--C--D--cycle);
draw(A--C);
draw(B--E);

label("$A$", A, N);
label("$B$", B, SW);
label("$C$", C, SE);
label("$D$", D, NE);
label("$E$", E, NE);
[/asy]

Then $BE = 24,$ so $AE = AC - CE = AC - \sqrt{51^2 - 24^2}.$  By the Pythagorean theorem on right triangle $ABE,$
\[AE^2 + BE^2 = AB^2.\]Substituting $AE = AC - \sqrt{51^2 - 24^2}$ and $BE = 24,$ we get
\[(AC - \sqrt{51^2 - 24^2})^2 + 24^2 = 51^2.\]Solving, we find $AC = \boxed{68}.$

